===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|abraiden|lang=enm}}, {{term|abreiden||to start up, awake, move, reproach|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|abregdan|ābreġdan|to move quickly, vibrate, draw, draw from, remove, unsheath, wrench, pull out, withdraw, take away, draw back, free from, draw up, raise, lift up, start up|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|gem-pro|uz-|out|lang=en}} + {{proto|gem-pro|title=|bregdanan|to move, swing|lang=en}}, from {{proto|ine-pro|bhrēḱ-||bhrēǵ-|to shine|lang=en}}, related to Dutch {{term|breien||to knit|lang=nl}}, German {{term|bretten||to knit|lang=de}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive|obsolete}} {{context|of a sword}} To [[wrench]] out.
